Wei Zhao and Jeff Beck and their colleagues provided wonderful descriptions of QA practices in large aggregators like the Ontario Scholars Portal or PubMed Central. Such aggregators are constrained to accept input from a wide variety of sources with wide variations in quality, but they try to produce unified interfaces. So the aggregators need to try to level the quality by bringing up the lower bound [
,
].

Sheila Morrissey and her colleagues at Portico showed how they extend their focus
         from the data that they are preserving to the systems they are using to preserve the
         data [

], and Jorge Williams, in the conference itself, pointed our tools in yet another
         direction, to validate not deployment packages, but whole RESTful services [

].

If you’re in the realm of stochastic methods, then you’re in the realm of sampling and exploratory data analysis and the techniques that Micah Dubinko talked about, using XQuery to get an overview of unfamiliar data [
]. Someone hands you a USB stick and says,
I need a summary. Now. Quick! What do you do? Well, hopefully you’ve internalized the techniques Micah Dubink described, because they will help you in that situation.

The more traditional way to grow a technology is to add functionality, and there the challenge is to add functionality in a way that feels like an organic development, feels like growth, and doesn’t feel to the technology adopters like a risky change. The organic development of XQuery in Mary Holstege’s talk on type introspection [
] exemplifies the kind of new functionality that will feel intuitively right to most users of the technology. I was similarly heartened to hear Abel Braaksma’s discussion of higher-order functions and other functional technologies in XSLT 3.0 [
]. Hervé Ruellan’s discussion of XML entropy seems to suggest ways to develop and evaluate compression mechanisms for marked-up documents [
].

But it’s not always a question of
us versus them. Sometimes within the same institution, there will be those who want to work with XML or C++ or C-sharp, and others who want to work with different notations. So, Ari Nordström’s example of finding ways to do things in the notation of your choice as a way of helping keep the peace within an organization is a message we can all take to heart.
]. Remember: good fences make good neighbors.

That makes literate programming one of the most challenging areas that we face, but it is also one of the most important because, going back to that QA symposium on Monday, if we really want to preserve our information, it’s not just the documents we have to be able to understand and preserve, but the systems that they are built to interact with. And so literate programming as a method of making our programs easier to understand and keeping the documentation in sync with the executable code is crucial. So what Sam Wilmott said, yes [
]. What David Lee and Norm Walsh said, yes [
,
]. What Matthew McCormick said, absolutely [
]. And Mario Blažević’s efforts to bring back SHORTREF and make it work in an environment very different from the SGML environment for which it was originally developed [
]? If that makes it easier to have natural notations for information, then it will help information longevity.
